League of Legends

League of Legends, on the competitive scene, is played as a 5v5 team game in which each player controls one hero. It’s the largest game in the MOBA genre, and is played for millions of dollars each year.

We can access detailed information about the matched played at any level through an API.

LoL: Sources

For general information about using the API

https://developer.riotgames.com/docs/lol

You need a Riot account. If you want to do more than the basic API stuff, you need to submit a proposal to Riot.

https://developer.riotgames.com/docs/portal#_getting-started

For specific API calls, see this link

https://developer.riotgames.com/apis

This is a very handy video series on the use of the API, last updated in early 2024.

https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLnnM9dgSdUvIe0MRJcjbzBaJWFHNJaOh1

LoL: Getting your API key

First we need to refresh our API key, because the basic developer one needs to be manually re-generated for every 24 hours you plan to use it. There are longer-lived keys for the development of applications and websites that regularly need data from Riot Games, but you need to propose a project to Riot Games for that higher level access.

To get this key, you simply need a Riot account. You don’t even need to play or install a game.

Technically, this key is supposed to remain secret because who has it can impersonate you. However, this key will have expired by the time this talk goes live.

To get a new API key: https://developer.riotgames.com/

my_api_key = "RGAPI-ca5c9e2d-ac68-4984-a6ee-658876685416"

LoL: Finding a specific match

We can get multiple pages from Diamond I, one of the highest tiers of play in the game.

my_tier = "DIAMOND"
my_div = "I"
my_region = "na1"

for(k in 1:5)
{

  api_call_url = paste0("https://",
                        my_region,
                        ".api.riotgames.com/lol/league/v4/entries/RANKED_SOLO_5x5/",
                        my_tier,"/",
                        my_div,"?page=",
                        k,"&api_key=",
                        my_api_key)
  
  this_page = fromJSON(api_call_url)
    
  if(k == 1)
  {
    all_pages = this_page
  }
  
  if(k > 1)
  {
    all_pages = rbind(all_pages, this_page)
    
  }
  
  Sys.sleep(2)
  
}

my_region = "americas"

api_call_url = paste0("https://",
                      my_region,
                      ".api.riotgames.com/riot/account/v1/accounts/by-riot-id/",

this_user =  fromJSON(api_call_url)

this_match_timeline =  fromJSON(api_call_url)

library(stringr)
event_df3$assist1 = NA
event_df3$assist2 = NA
event_df3$assist3 = NA
event_df3$assist4 = NA
for(rownum in 1:nrow(event_df3))
{
  if(length(event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]]) >= 1)
  {
    event_df3$assist1[rownum] = event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]][1]
  }

  if(length(event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]]) >= 2)
  {
    event_df3$assist2[rownum] = event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]][2]
  }
  
  if(length(event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]]) >= 3)
  {
    event_df3$assist3[rownum] = event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]][3]
  }
  
  if(length(event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]]) >= 4)
  {
    event_df3$assist4[rownum] = event_df3$assistingParticipantIds[[rownum]][4]
  }
}

event_df3$assistingParticipantIds = NULL

Starcraft 2

Starcraft 2 is (one of) the biggest real time strategy games. It’s typically played, at the competitive level, as a 1v1 affair with each play controlling an army. Despite its age and the general lack of continued support for the game from its creator, Blizzard, it remains a popular eSport.

You can get basic information about ranked players from a Blizzard API, and you can get detailed game timelines from published .sc2replay files, such as those available at the website Spawningtool.

Starcraft 2: Getting a game timeline

We can get professional level gameplay from the webpage: https://lotv.spawningtool.com/replays/?pro_only=on

We can get the .sc2replay file for a match between Lambo (playing as a Zerg army) and Clem (playing as Terran) on June 11, 2024 at https://lotv.spawningtool.com/83884/

This match was played on the Crimson Court battlefield, and took 11 minutes and 42 seconds.

Starcraft 2: Parsing the .sc2replay file

There is a package called sc2reader available in Python to take sc2replay files and get individual events from them. However, this package has not been updated in 8 or more years. To use it, I used to the following Python code.

The documation for the package is at https://sc2reader.readthedocs.io/en/latest/articles/gettingstarted.html

import sc2reader
import pprint


replay = sc2reader.load_replay('lambo_v_clem.SC2Replay', load_map=True)
replay.load_map()


# Release version and game length info. Nothing else
replay0 = sc2reader.load_replay('lambo_v_clem.SC2Replay', load_level=0)

# Also loads game details: map, speed, time played, etc
replay1 = sc2reader.load_replay('lambo_v_clem.SC2Replay', load_level=1)

# Also loads players and chat events:
replay2 = sc2reader.load_replay('lambo_v_clem.SC2Replay', load_level=2)

# Also loads tracker events:
replay3 = sc2reader.load_replay('lambo_v_clem.SC2Replay', load_level=3)

#for event in replay3.events:
#    print('{0} => {1}: {2}').format(event.pid,event.name, event.time)

# Also loads game events:
replay4 = sc2reader.load_replay('lambo_v_clem.SC2Replay', load_level=4)

f = open("output.txt", "a")
print(replay4.events, file=f)
f.close()

Starcraft 2: Parsing the .sc2replay file

Luke Holroyd (ZephyrBlu) made an Sc2 parser in Python as well.

The code is here

https://github.com/ZephyrBlu/zephyrus-sc2-parser

The documentation is here

https://gist.github.com/ZephyrBlu/f24ea40eb38127640194691959f957f6

In Python, I used the following code to get a JSON file of the match details.

from zephyrus_sc2_parser import parse_replay
import json

replay = parse_replay("lambo_v_clem.SC2Replay")

json_timeline = json.dumps(replay.timeline)
json_summary = json.dumps(replay.summary)


f = open("output_timeline_json.txt", "a")
print(json_timeline, file=f)
f.close()

f = open("output_summary_json.txt", "a")
print(json_summary, file=f)
f.close()

Starcraft 2: Reading the game timeline

The Zerg army depends on territory covered in a biological substance called ‘creep’. One indicator of how strong a Zerg army is is the percentage of the map that is currently covered in creep. We can graph that over time.

creep_cover_pct = rep(NA, length(tl1$race$creep$coverage))
creep_cover_tiles = rep(NA, length(tl1$race$creep$coverage))

for(k in 1:length(creep_cover_pct))
{
  creep_cover_pct[k] = tl1$race$creep$coverage[[k]][1]
  creep_cover_tiles[k] = tl1$race$creep$coverage[[k]][2]
  
}  

seconds = tl1$gameloop / 112 * 5
plot(y = creep_cover_pct, x=seconds, type="l", lwd=3)

Starcraft 2: Reading the game timeline

There are two types of resources: minerals and gas. Adding up the (mineral + gas) cost of every unit for each player gives us a rough measure of army strength over time. We can plot this for both players.

tl1_army = timeline$One$army_value
tl2_army = timeline$Two$army_value
tl1_army$player = "Lambo (Zerg)"
tl2_army$player = "Clem (Terran)"

army_values = rbind(tl1_army, tl2_army) 
army_values$time = timeline$One$gameloop / 112 * 5
army_values$total = army_values$minerals + army_values$gas

g = ggplot(data=army_values, aes(x=time, y=total, 
                                 group=player, color=player)) + 
    geom_line(lwd=3)

plot(g)

Starcraft 2: Future work

(Suggestions from William Davis)

  • Probably the simplest thing to look into is army value and worker value. Workers are worth future value and army is current assets. If the disparity of army value becomes too great one player wins.
  • There is defenders advantage but it scales poorly, starts at a flat number and scales linearly while army values lethality will scale exponentially.
  • Army values exponential value will be more linked to gas value rather than minerals.
  • EAPM (effective actions per minute) probably has linear returns on success up to a point and then it has diminishing returns.

Chess and the PGN format

Chess and the PGN format

Chess games are typically stored in the Portable Game Notation (PGN) format.

First, the format looks a lot like that of JSON or XML. We’re going to start by tackling it manually with text analysis. Next week is all about text analysis, but let’s break down what we can. What can we get from this, reading it as a human?

Chess and the PGN format

We have the webpage for the event, the match, and some other metadata like the players and (starting) time of the game. We can also see that everything in these first 17 lines is of the format [VARNAME “data”].

We could extract that with the stringr package.

readLines() pulls in data to R verbatim. This file is the same example game four times.

Chess and the PGN format

Chess and the PGN format

That worked great for the game metadata, but not the moves. Let’s find a way to isolate the moves. The regular expression ^\\[.*\\]$ means…

  • ^ means “Starts with”
  • \\[ First character is literally a [. The backslash \ is an escape character, and we need to double-escape when using str_xxx functions because they call to another more primitive called grep.
  • . is a wildcard. It could be ANY character
  • * is “any number of”, including zero. So .* means any string of any length
  • \\] is the character at the end of the wildcard string.
  • $ means “ends with”, so anything with both ^ and $ implies the entire string must match the pattern.

Chess and the PGN format

Therefore, the regular expression ^\\[.*\\]$ means… “Starts with [, and ends with ]”

is_metadata = str_detect(pgn_ex, "^\\[.*\\]$")

Great! Now for the hard part: How to parse this?

pgn_ex[20:24]
## [1] "1. e4 { [%eval 0.17] [%clk 0:00:30] } 1... c5 { [%eval 0.19] [%clk 0:00:30] }"   
## [2] "2. Nf3 { [%eval 0.25] [%clk 0:00:29] } 2... Nc6 { [%eval 0.33] [%clk 0:00:30] }" 
## [3] "3. Bc4 { [%eval -0.13] [%clk 0:00:28] } 3... e6 { [%eval -0.04] [%clk 0:00:30] }"
## [4] "4. c3 { [%eval -0.4] [%clk 0:00:27] } 4... b5? { [%eval 1.18] [%clk 0:00:30] }"  
## [5] "5. Bb3?! { [%eval 0.21] [%clk 0:00:26] } 5... c4 { [%eval 0.32] [%clk 0:00:29] }"

The format is

MOVENUM. WHITEMOVE { [%eval EVAL] [%clk CLOCK TIME]} MOVENUM... BLACKMOVE { [%eval EVAL] [%clk CLOCK TIME]}
